Phase 3 ‚Äî Execution & Commercialization
Purpose

Phase 3 defines where execution begins and where money changes hands for the Event-First UAV architecture.

Everything prior to Phase 3 (Phase 0, Phase 1, Phase 2) exists to support reasoning, feasibility framing, and architectural clarity.
Phase 3 is the boundary where theory turns into real-world action.

If you cross this boundary without a license, you are out of bounds.

What Phase 3 Is

Phase 3 is:

Authorization to execute the Event-First UAV architecture

The legal and commercial transition point

The point at which theory may be applied to reality

The sole place where execution rights are granted

Phase 3 is not additional technical content.
It is permission.

Relationship to Other Phases

Phase 0 ‚Äî Permission to exist (problem framing, non-claims)

Phase 1 ‚Äî Permission to test (bounded prototypes, assumptions)

Phase 2 ‚Äî Permission to think (theory-only, TEL-1.0)

Phase 3 ‚Äî Permission to execute (this phase)

Each phase is legally independent.

Possession of Phase 0, Phase 1, or Phase 2 materials does not grant execution rights.

Execution Definition (Non-Negotiable)

For purposes of this repository, execution includes any of the following:

Building or prototyping hardware

Flight testing or ground testing

Simulation intended to inform implementation

Integration into an existing UAV system

Use in proposals, bids, grants, or contracts

Commercial or government deployment

Internal programs intended to lead to deployment

Derivative works intended for real-world use

Intent does not matter. Outcome controls.

If the work touches reality, it is execution.

Execution License

Any execution of the Event-First UAV architecture requires a Phase 3 Execution License.

Base terms:

Execution license fee: $5,000 USD (one-time)

Grants permission to execute Phase 2 theory

Covers internal use or external deployment

Additional scope, exclusivity, or royalty terms (if any) are negotiated separately

Licenses are granted in writing only

No implied licenses exist.

What the License Buys You

The execution license replaces:

Internal architectural reinvention

Months of CONOPS debate

Event-trigger logic argumentation

Failure-mode philosophy disputes

Sensor-vs-platform priority churn

You are paying to skip indecision, not to buy hardware.

Execution risk remains entirely yours.

What Counts as Commercialization

The following are considered commercialization and require a Phase 3 execution license:

Selling systems, subsystems, or services based on this architecture

Including the architecture in paid contracts or programs

Using the architecture to support revenue-generating operations

Government or defense program use

Integration into products offered to customers

Commercialization does not require profit to trigger licensing.

What Does Not Count as Commercialization

The following do not require a Phase 3 execution license:

Reading or reviewing Phase 3 text

Internal business evaluation

Budgetary or program planning

Non-executing academic discussion

Conceptual comparison to other architectures

Execution is the trigger, not curiosity.

